SIMPLE: steerage
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Steerage
<hw>Steer"age</hw> <pr>(st⟦emac⟧r"⟦asl⟧j ; 48)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The act or practice of steering, or directing; <as>as,
the <ex>steerage</ex> of a ship</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He left the city, and, in a most tempestuous season, forsook the
helm and <qex>steerage</qex> of the commonwealth.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The effect of the
helm on a ship; the manner in which an individual ship is affected by
the helm.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>The hinder part of a vessel; the
stern.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark> <au>Swift.</au> <sd>(c)</sd>
<def>Properly, the space in the after part of a vessel, under the cabin,
but used generally to indicate any part of a vessel having the poorest
accommodations and occupied by passengers paying the lowest rate of
fare.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Direction; regulation; management;
guidance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He that hath the <qex>steerage</qex> of my course.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That by which a course is directed.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here he hung on high,⟦br⟧
The <qex>steerage</qex> of his wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Steerage passenger</b></col>, <cd>a passenger who takes
passage in the steerage of a vessel.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Steerageway</ent>⟦br⟧
